<div class="container my-5">
  <h1>About the Book Library Project</h1>

  <section class="mt-4">
    <h2>Dataset Description</h2>
    <p>
      This project uses the <strong>Open Library API</strong> as its primary data source. Open Library provides extensive data about books, authors, genres, and publishing information. For each book, we gather data such as:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Book title</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Cover image</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Published year</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Author information</strong> (name, birthdate)</li>
      <li><strong>Genre information</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The data is structured into multiple related tables:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Authors</strong>: id, name, birth_date</li>
      <li><strong>Books</strong>: id, title, published_year, cover_url, author_id (Foreign Key)</li>
      <li><strong>Genres</strong>: id, name</li>
      <li><strong>BookGenres</strong> (Join Table): id, book_id, genre_id (Foreign Keys)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Relationships include:
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Authors to Books</strong>: One-to-many (An author has many books)</li>
        <li><strong>Books to Genres</strong>: Many-to-many (A book can have multiple genres, and genres can have multiple books)</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

